    en: "When a NY hospital or nursing home patient lacks the capacity to make medical decisions and has no health care proxy, New York's Family Health Care Decisions Act (FHCDA) at NY Public Health Law Article 29-CC determines who can make decisions on the patient's behalf. The law sets a hierarchy of surrogate decision-makers: court-appointed guardian first, then spouse or domestic partner, then adult child, then parent, then sibling, then close friend. The surrogate's authority is broad but not unlimited — life-sustaining treatment decisions require additional clinical findings."
